	dprr:hasNoteText "By 102. p. 746, footnote 243" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/3597> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #3597" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Termed {Gr} in IG 5.1.1432,\n     in Messenia; so probably Proconsul in Macedonia." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/3560> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #3560" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Cic. Font. 24; Val. Max. 8.5.2." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/3559> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #3559" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Memmius, a candidate for the consulship of 99, must have held the praetorship by 102; but the close association of his trial for extortion with that of Fimbria, with Scaurus witnessing against both, indicates that the consulship of the one and the praetorship of the other were probably contemporary. See 103, Promagistrates." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/3438> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #3438" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Forced the decision to make war on Jugurtha. Accused the Consul Bestia, Scaurus, and other nobles of accepting bribes from the King, and had the latter summoned to Rome under safe-conduct for questioning, but was impeded in his questioning of the King by the veto of his colleague Baebius (Sall. Iug. 27.1-5; 30-34; cf. Liv. Per. 64)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/3143> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #3143" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "All served under Scipio at Numantia (Memmius: Frontin. Str. 4.1.1; Plut. Apophth. Scip. Min. 17. Rutilius: App. Ib. 88; Cic. Rep. 1.17; Suidas, s. v. {Gr}. Asellio: Gell. 2.13.3, the historian. Gracchus: Plut. TG 13.1, not specifically termed Tr. Mil.)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/3142> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #3142" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/4> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "With Scipio were also C. Marius and C. Lucilius (Vell. 2.9.4, on Lucilius; Vell. 2.9.4; Val Max. 8.15.7; Plut. Mar. 3.2-4, and 13.2, on Marius). Marius' position is uncertain, perhaps an eques (Plut. Mar. 13.2), for this service precedes his military tribunate (Sall. Iug. 63.3). Lucilius is termed an eques but as the brother, and later the brother-in-law also, of a senator, could have had an official positio on Scipio's staff (see Cichorius, Untersuch. Lucil. 14ff., 24ff.)." .
